Recently we have created unique index on column AUTHOR_NAME in table AUTHOR. By default MySQL uses case insensitive indexes, thus it is not possible to insert 2 rows, one with value "unknown" and other with "Unknown" - this type of data is present in our internal exports.

What customer should know is that it is preferable/required? to create database with collation utf8_bin

{code:sql}
CREATE DATABASE bamboodb CHARACTER SET utf8 COLLATE utf8_bin;
{code}

I think that these 2 pages should be updated:
http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/MySQL+5.x
http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Creating+an+external+database+for+Bamboo

We also need to update the following page according to the comments below by Marcin:
http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Microsoft+SQL+Server+2005+and+2008

If a standalone Jira issue key is included in a changelist comment (we are using Perforce), and then occurs again in a URL inside the same comment -- it will replace the in-URL version and break the link. It is conflicting with htmlUtils.getTextAsHtml.

A sample comment in which this may occur:
{code}
JIRA-1234
http://jira/browse/JIRA-1234
I fixed the bug.
{code}

This will wind up getting translated into something like:
{code}
<a title="View this issue" class="jiraLinkIcon" href="http://jira/browse/JIRA-1234?page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.ext.bamboo%3Abamboo-build-results-tabpanel" id="viewIssueInJira:JIRA-1234">JIRA-1234</a><br/>
<a href="http://jira/browse/<a title="View this issue" class="jiraLinkIcon" href="http://jira/browse/JIRA-1234?page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.ext.bamboo%3Abamboo-build-results-tabpanel" id="viewIssueInJira:JIRA-1234">JIRA-1234</a>">http://jira/browse/<a title="View this issue" class="jiraLinkIcon" href="http://jira/browse/JIRA-1234?page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.ext.bamboo%3Abamboo-build-results-tabpanel" id="viewIssueInJira:JIRA-1234">JIRA-1234</a></a><br/>I fixed the bug.
{code}

This does not occur if the in-URL is the only occurrence (as it will not be found by JiraIssueUtils.findIssueKeysInText).

I have worked around this issue by including " and < in the JiraIssueUtils.REPLACE_KEY_REGEX_END pattern -- but this will obviously prevent things like:

{code}
As per meeting: "Correct outstanding issue in JIRA-1234"
{code}

But its quite a stretch to find a natural way to squeeze a " after the issue key in a check-in comment -- so I'm not expecting that to be a problem for me at least. (This would probably wind up being "linked" -- in the related issues sense -- but not have a hyperlink attached to it... no? I'm not quite ambitious enough to check...)

